        <section id="methodology">
            <h2>Methodology</h2>
            <p>Our bond ETF comparison uses real-time and historical pricing data gathered from financial market APIs. We curated a list of the most popular and highly-traded ETFs across various bond sectors: Total Bond Market (BND, AGG), Corporate (LQD, VCIT), Treasuries (SHY, IEF, TLT), TIPS (TIP, SCHP), Municipals (MUB), and High-Yield (HYG, JNK).</p>
            <p><strong>Yield:</strong> Represents the trailing 12-month dividend yield.<br>
            <strong>Performance Returns:</strong> Calculated using adjusted close prices to account for dividends and splits.<br>
            <strong>AUM:</strong> Total Assets Under Management, providing a proxy for liquidity and fund stability.</p>
        </section>

        <section id="faq">
            <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
            <div class="faq-item">
                <div class="faq-q">What is the best bond ETF for 2026?</div>
                <div class="faq-a">The best bond ETF depends on your goals. BND and AGG offer broad total bond market exposure, while SHY or IEF are better for conservative Treasury holdings. For higher income, HYG or JNK provide high-yield exposure.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="faq-item">
                <div class="faq-q">BND vs AGG: Which is better?</div>
                <div class="faq-a">BND (Vanguard) and AGG (iShares) track similar broad bond indices and have nearly identical expense ratios. Performance is typically very close, making them largely interchangeable for most portfolios.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="faq-item">
                <div class="faq-q">What is the best treasury ETF?</div>
                <div class="faq-a">For short-term Treasuries, SHY is highly popular. For intermediate-term, IEF is a strong choice. For long-term duration, TLT provides significant exposure, though with higher price volatility.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="faq-item">
                <div class="faq-q">What is the best corporate bond ETF?</div>
                <div class="faq-a">LQD is the most liquid and popular ETF for investment-grade corporate bonds. VCIT is another excellent choice for intermediate-term corporate bonds with a low expense ratio.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="faq-item">
                <div class="faq-q">Are bond ETFs a good investment right now?</div>
                <div class="faq-a">Bond ETFs can provide steady income and portfolio diversification. Yields fluctuate with Fed policy, but bonds generally offer stability compared to equities, making them a staple in balanced portfolios.</div>
            </div>
        </section>

